Retrieve Data

Retrieve and download data from Github

# Retrieve data from Github
urlfile <- "https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ttknapp/ist687-finalprojectdata/master/DSV_no_names.csv"
destinationfile <- "ist687_finalprojectdata.csv" 
DetailedStudentData<-download.file(urlfile, destinationfile, method = "curl")

# Read downloaded CSV
DetailedStudentData <- read.csv("ist687_finalprojectdata.csv", header = TRUE,
                                sep = ",",stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Cleaning up data

Clean up data by removing unneeded rows/columns, separating some columns, and creating a new column called TimeDifferential

# Removing some columns
DetailedStudentData<-DetailedStudentData[,-3:-4]

# separating Campus.ID into different columns
DetailedStudentData <- separate(DetailedStudentData, col = Campus.ID, 
                       into = c("Campus", "StudentLabelfiveOfour", "Delete Column",
                            "TestfiveOfour", "DeleteTwo", "TestSPED", "TestELSPED"),
                       sep = " | ")

# Removing some newly created columns
DetailedStudentData <-DetailedStudentData[c(-3,-5)]

# Function to remove unnecessary information in columns
Gsubber <- function(Z) 
{
  Z <-gsub("[|]","",Z)
  Z <-gsub ("RP3","", Z)
  Z <-gsub ("APP","", Z)
  Z <-gsub ("DRA","", Z)
  Z <-gsub ("SHRD","", Z)
  Z <-gsub ("Lite","", Z)
  Z <-gsub ("PRA","", Z)
  return((Z))
  }
DetailedStudentData$StudentLabel <- Gsubber(
  DetailedStudentData$StudentLabelfiveOfour)
DetailedStudentData$StudentLabel2 <- Gsubber(DetailedStudentData$TestSPED)
DetailedStudentData$StudentLabel3 <- Gsubber(DetailedStudentData$TestELSPED)
DetailedStudentData$StudentLabel4 <- Gsubber(DetailedStudentData$TestfiveOfour)
DetailedStudentData <- DetailedStudentData[,-2:-5]
DetailedStudentData <- unite(
  DetailedStudentData,StudentLabel,StudentLabel2,StudentLabel3,StudentLabel4)

# Function to remove more unnecessary information in columns
dOUBLEsubber <- function(Z) 
{
  Z <-gsub("__","",Z)
  Z <-gsub ("_EL_","EL", Z)
  Z <-gsub ("_SPED_","SPED", Z)
  Z <- gsub("__","",Z)
  Z <-gsub("NA","",Z)
  Z <-gsub("__","CORE",Z)
  Z <-gsub("SPEDCORE","SPED",Z)
  return(Z)
}
DetailedStudentData$StudentLabel <- dOUBLEsubber(DetailedStudentData$StudentLabel)

# Designate DetailedStudentData as a data frame
DetailedStudentData <- as.data.frame(DetailedStudentData)

# Rename Columns
colnames(DetailedStudentData) <- c("Campus", "Student.ID", "Course.Name", "Unit", "Type", "Assignment", "Opened.Date", "TurnedIn.Date", "Time.Spent", "Assignment.Score", "Unit.Score", "Total.Score", "Student.Label")

# Remove rows with missing data
DetailedStudentData <-DetailedStudentData[-c(166:167, 171, 176, 179),]

# Convert Time.Spent times to datetime
DetailedStudentData$Time.Spent <- as.POSIXct(DetailedStudentData$Time.Spent,format="%M:%S")

# Create new data frame so we keep our other data untouched
fullData <- DetailedStudentData

# Convert Opened and Turned In dates to datetime
fullData$Opened.Date <- as.Date(fullData$Opened.Date, "%m/%d/%Y")
fullData$TurnedIn.Date <- as.Date(fullData$TurnedIn.Date, "%m/%d/%Y")


# Subtract Opened and Turned In dates in order to find the total time elapsed in days (time differential)
fullData$TimeDifferential <- as.numeric(fullData$TurnedIn.Date - fullData$Opened.Date)
# Add 1 to TimeDifferential in order to make more conceptual sense 
fullData$TimeDifferential <- fullData$TimeDifferential + 1

Aggregate Students, Part 1

Aggregate the students and create a new column to show students Movement from one unit to another

# Create new dataframe to edit
AggDF <- fullData
# Remove unnecessary columns
AggDF <-AggDF[-c(1,3:9,13)]
# Aggregate data by student and find the mean of each students' time differential
AggDF <- aggregate(AggDF, by = list (AggDF$Student.ID), mean, na.rm=TRUE)
AggDF <- AggDF[,-1]
colnames(AggDF)[2] <- "Avg.Assignment.Score"
colnames(AggDF)[3] <- "Avg.Unit.Score"
colnames(AggDF)[4] <- "Avg.Total.Score"

# Create new dataframe for Units Completed by grouping by Student.ID and subtracting the end unit from the beginning unit 
UnitsCompleted <- fullData %>%
  group_by(Student.ID)%>%
  summarise(max(Unit), min(Unit))
colnames(UnitsCompleted)<- c("Student", "Beg", "End")
# Create new column for units completed called Movement
UnitsCompleted$Movement <- UnitsCompleted$Beg - UnitsCompleted$End
# Find mean units completed for all students
mean(UnitsCompleted$Movement)
## [1] 1.5

Aggregate Students, Part 2

Aggregate the students for use in later visualizations

# Aggregate student data in order to view individual students in separate data frame
second <- function(x){
  if (length(x) == 1)
    return(x)
  return(sort(x, decreasing =  TRUE)[2])
}
agg <- aggregate(DetailedStudentData,
                 by = list (DetailedStudentData$Student.ID,DetailedStudentData$Student.Label),
                 FUN = second)
# Remove unnecessary columns
agg <- agg[-c(1:2)]


# Separate time from date & make time usable for arithmetic 
CleanStart <- data.frame(do.call("rbind",strsplit(as.character(agg$Opened.Date), " ", fixed = TRUE)))
CleanEnd <-data.frame(do.call("rbind", strsplit(as.character(agg$TurnedIn.Date)," ", fixed = TRUE)))
names(CleanStart) <- c("StartDate","StartTime")
names(CleanEnd) <- c("EndDate", "EndTime")
AddingColumns <- cbind(CleanStart, CleanEnd)
AddingColumns$StartDate <- as.Date(AddingColumns$StartDate, "%m/%d/%Y")
AddingColumns$EndDate <- as.Date(AddingColumns$EndDate, "%m/%d/%Y")
# Subtract Start and End dates in order to find the total time elapsed in days
AddingColumns$TimeDifferential <- as.numeric(AddingColumns$StartDate - AddingColumns$EndDate)
# Add 1 and remove negatives to TimeDifferential in order to make more conceptual sense 
AddingColumns$TimeDifferential <- (AddingColumns$TimeDifferential*-1) + 1

KSVM Modeling

Create a KSVM model in order to train our data to predict Success (movement from one unit to another)

# Add Movement column to AggDF
AggDF$Movement <- UnitsCompleted$Movement
# Add Success column to AggDF to designate Success vs noSuccess
# We define "Success" as having any movement to another unit
AggDF$Success <- as.factor(ifelse(AggDF$Movement > 0,"Success","noSuccess"))
AggDF <- AggDF[,-6]

# KSVM
dim(AggDF)
## [1] 38  6
table(AggDF$Success)
## 
## noSuccess   Success 
##        13        25
randIndex <- sample(1:dim(AggDF)[1])
head(randIndex)
## [1]  8  2 20  6 16 24
cutPoint2_3 <- floor(2 * dim(AggDF)[1]/3)
trainData <- AggDF[randIndex[1:cutPoint2_3],]
testData <- AggDF[randIndex[(cutPoint2_3+1):dim(AggDF)[1]],]
svmOutput <- ksvm(Success ~ Avg.Total.Score, data=trainData, kernel = "rbfdot",kpar="automatic",C=50,cross=3, prob.model=TRUE)
svmOutput
## Support Vector Machine object of class "ksvm" 
## 
## SV type: C-svc  (classification) 
##  parameter : cost C = 50 
## 
## Gaussian Radial Basis kernel function. 
##  Hyperparameter : sigma =  15.7696086440978 
## 
## Number of Support Vectors : 12 
## 
## Objective Function Value : -98.7389 
## Training error : 0.04 
## Cross validation error : 0.203704 
## Probability model included.
hist(alpha(svmOutput)[[1]])

svmPred <- predict(svmOutput, testData, type = "votes")
compTable <- data.frame(testData[,6],svmPred[1,])
table(compTable)
##              svmPred.1...
## testData...6. 0 1
##     noSuccess 3 1
##     Success   9 0

# Visualization #1: Histogram of Score
qplot(Assignment.Score, data = DetailedStudentData, binwidth = 2)

# Description 1: A histogram showing the relationship between score and number of assignments turned in.
# The x-axis shows the score while the y-axis shows the number of assignments turned in with such score.

# Interpretation 1: We noticed that most assignments were scored at 100%, implying mostly good performance overall. 
# Though, we also observed that the second largest concentration of assignment scores was around 70%, which shows that there is a moderate number of assignments that are just barely being mastered and passed.
# This observation may become more valuable for us as we continue our analysis.



# Visualization #2: Categories of Students Per Assignment

        horiz = TRUE,
        las = 1,
        col = c("dimgray", "khaki","grey", "indianred"),
        border = NA,
        main = "Categories of Students\n Per Assignment",
        xlab = "Number of Assignments Turned In")

# Description 2: A horizontal bar plot showing the relationship between categories of students and number of assignments submitted.
# The x-axis shows the number of assignments submitted and the y-axis shows the categories of students (CORE, EL, SPED, 504).

# Interpretation 2: This visual showcases the sharp disparities among the 4 categories of students. 
# CORE students, whom face no learning disabilities or challenges turned in more assignments than students from any other group. 
# We expected this correlation, as the other categories of students face learning obstacles that may inhibit their ability to keep up with course rigor.

# Description 10: A box plot showing the relationship between Score and Percent Change
# The x-axis shows the Score received while the y-axis shows the Percent Change.

# Interpretation 10: The middle 50% of scores are between ~75% and just under ~95% showing that half the population of students are at least passing. 
# The y-axis shows a deviation of about .4 in either positive or negative direction pointing to a moderate distribution of the interquartile range of scores.



# Visualization #11: Regression of Assignment Score and Unit Score
plot(DetailedStudentData$Unit.Score,DetailedStudentData$Assignment.Score, xlab = "Unit.Score", ylab = "Assignment Score", las =2) 
abline(lm(Unit.Score~Assignment.Score, data = DetailedStudentData), col='red')

# Description 11: A regression showing the relationship between Score and Unit Score
# The x-axis shows Unit Score while the y-axis shows Score.

# Interpretation 11: There is a strong positive relationship given that the unit score is a subset of the total score. 
# The two scores are therefore dependent on one another and prove that our data is behaving as expected.



# Visualization #12: Violin Plot
x1 <- agg$Unit[agg$Student.Label == "CORE"]
x2 <- agg$Unit[agg$Student.Label == "SPED"]
x3 <- agg$Unit[agg$Student.Label == "504"]
x4 <- agg$Unit[agg$Student.Label == "EL"]
vioplot(x1, x2, x3, x4, names =c ("CORE", "SPED", "504", "EL"),
        col = "deeppink1", main = "Units Completed/Student Label")

# Description 12: The violin plot is a mixture of a boxplot and density plot showing the relationship between Student Label and Units Completed.
# The x-axis shows Student Label while the y-axis shows Units Completed

# Interpretation 12: It appears that the highest range of Units Completed (and therefore the most highly achieving students) are completed by CORE students.
# CORE students also have a median of 2 Units Completed with the lower quantile being 1 and upper quantile being 3 units. 
# The majority of students in CORE complete 1-2 units.
# Next highest range of Units Completed are completed by SPED students (1-4 Units) with a median of 1 Unit completed. 
# The majority of SPED students complete 1-2 units, but they appear to have a higher density of students completing Units 3 and 4 than CORE students.
# Some students begin the new semester carrying over from the prior semester, which is why they start at the 3rd Unit in this plot in the EL Student Label.
# EL students have a median of Unit 4 completion. 
# The Unit Completion data for 504 students was not substantial enough to chart on this graph.
